missions and planets?

00:26:23.695 --> 00:26:24.320
ALAN STERN: Oh.

00:26:24.320 --> 00:26:26.101
Well, both.

00:26:26.101 --> 00:26:26.600
Both.

00:26:26.600 --> 00:26:28.430
And we actually almost-- we
had a debate about whether--

00:26:28.430 --> 00:26:30.013
I mean, there's more
been one mission,

00:26:30.013 --> 00:26:31.401
so I would just say first.

00:26:31.401 --> 00:26:32.900
It's just the epic
mission of Pluto.

00:26:32.900 --> 00:26:35.750
Isn't that enough?

00:26:35.750 --> 00:26:38.790
But first is one of those words
that it's like an SEO thing,

00:26:38.790 --> 00:26:39.290
right?

00:26:39.290 --> 00:26:41.480
It's going to get
people to look at it.

00:26:41.480 --> 00:26:45.410
But we do expect that there
will be more missions because we

00:26:45.410 --> 00:26:50.330
originally thought that we
could go in with 21st century

00:26:50.330 --> 00:26:53.150
instrumentation and
accomplish, and we did,

00:26:53.150 --> 00:26:55.340
about the equivalent of
the first 20 years of Mars

00:26:55.340 --> 00:26:58.460
exploration in one fell swoop.

00:26:58.460 --> 00:26:59.570
And we did.

00:26:59.570 --> 00:27:04.850
But we learned many things
that make my head hurt.

00:27:04.850 --> 00:27:09.020
And so we're working very hard
to see an orbiter fly there

00:27:09.020 --> 00:27:09.810
and follow up.

00:27:09.810 --> 00:27:12.764
And I think there'll be, now,
other missions to small planets

00:27:12.764 --> 00:27:14.180
in the Kuiper Belt
because we want

00:27:14.180 --> 00:27:16.660
to sample the diversity
of this new population.

00:27:16.660 --> 00:27:18.160
I think if Pluto
is that interesting

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:21.040
and some of the things we know
from ground-based and Hubble,

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:24.000
soon we'll know from James Webb.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.060
I think that we'll also
want to look at some

00:27:26.060 --> 00:27:28.080
of the others for comparison.

00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:30.140
So I expect there'll
be a lot more of this.

00:27:30.140 --> 00:27:31.640
Yes.

00:27:31.640 --> 00:27:34.500
AUDIENCE: At the risk of being
a little bit obnoxious here,

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:37.840
I'd like you to weigh on
the merits of manned space

00:27:37.840 --> 00:27:40.680
exploration versus
robotic space exploration.

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:44.490
And I ask this in
earnest because we,

00:27:44.490 --> 00:27:48.550
living in a quasi-democratic
country, perhaps, as citizens,

00:27:48.550 --> 00:27:50.860
get to weigh in on where
we put our dollars.

00:27:50.860 --> 00:27:53.100
Do you think the public's
perception of this

00:27:53.100 --> 00:27:55.134
is aligned with your
perception of this?

00:27:55.134 --> 00:27:57.050
ALAN STERN: Well, that's
a different question.

00:27:57.050 --> 00:27:58.790
But I will weigh in.

00:27:58.790 --> 00:28:00.530
So you said weigh
in on the merits

00:28:00.530 --> 00:28:06.290
of robotic spaceflight versus
human space flight Right.

00:28:06.290 --> 00:28:07.880
So I might translate
that question

00:28:07.880 --> 00:28:08.963
to an equivalent question.

00:28:08.963 --> 00:28:13.770
Would you please weigh in for
me on the merits of a knife,

00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:16.405
a fork, and spoon at the table?

00:28:16.405 --> 00:28:18.030
My point is they're
all different tools

00:28:18.030 --> 00:28:18.988
for different purposes.

00:28:18.988 --> 00:28:21.450
And at the table, you
really need all three.

00:28:21.450 --> 00:28:23.910
It's really hard to do
your soup with a fork,

00:28:23.910 --> 00:28:27.120
and it's really hard to
cut your steak with just

00:28:27.120 --> 00:28:28.980
the spoon or the fork.

00:28:28.980 --> 00:28:34.020
And so human space flight
and robotic space flight

00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:37.480
are really very different tools.

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:40.650
I don't know anybody
in this time that

00:28:40.650 --> 00:28:42.870
would say you need
human space flight

00:28:42.870 --> 00:28:45.840
to do weather satellites and
communications satellites

00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:47.430
and a lot of the applications.

00:28:47.430 --> 00:28:50.970
But it's still the case that
humans make much better field

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:55.560
analysis teams than the
rovers that we have now.

00:28:55.560 --> 00:28:59.910
Apollo teams would cover about
as much ground scientifically

00:28:59.910 --> 00:29:02.340
in a three-day expedition
as a Rover mission can

00:29:02.340 --> 00:29:04.410
in five years.

00:29:04.410 --> 00:29:08.220
And they can make on the spot
discoveries that robots can't.

00:29:08.220 --> 00:29:10.067
So I think we need
all the tools.

00:29:10.067 --> 00:29:12.150
And you know, we're not
going to be sending people

00:29:12.150 --> 00:29:15.300
to Pluto anytime soon.

00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:17.730
But on the other hand, at
places like the moon and Mars,

00:29:17.730 --> 00:29:20.630
and maybe series and
smaller asteroids,

00:29:20.630 --> 00:29:23.230
the humans can really push
the pedal to the metal.

00:29:23.230 --> 00:29:25.890
And the humans do something--
even though New Horizons

00:29:25.890 --> 00:29:29.430
was a good example of
being inspirational,

00:29:29.430 --> 00:29:31.510
it's hard for the
23rd mission to Mars,

00:29:31.510 --> 00:29:35.130
for that particular robot to
really light people's fire,

00:29:35.130 --> 00:29:40.110
whereas when we
send men and women,

00:29:40.110 --> 00:29:45.010
it will be unbelievable in
terms of the worldwide response.

00:29:45.010 --> 00:29:46.710
And that's what fuels
the tech economy.

00:29:46.710 --> 00:29:50.000
You know, space is the gateway
drug to engineering and science

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:50.500
careers.

00:29:50.500 --> 00:29:54.460
Well, dinosaurs, too, but
dinosaurs always lose.

00:29:54.460 --> 00:29:56.150
So it's really space.

00:29:56.150 --> 00:29:56.700
Who else?

00:29:56.700 --> 00:29:58.200
Yes.

00:29:58.200 --> 00:30:00.090
AUDIENCE: How long did
it take after launch

00:30:00.090 --> 00:30:04.750
for you to read a paper
or see a tech report

00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:06.865
and wish that was
something you had had?

00:30:06.865 --> 00:30:07.740
ALAN STERN: On board?

00:30:07.740 --> 00:30:08.323
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:30:10.900 --> 00:30:12.800
ALAN STERN: So we've
talked about that, too.

00:30:12.800 --> 00:30:16.960
And so there are two
ways to look at that.

00:30:16.960 --> 00:30:19.330
And the only realistic
way to look at it is,

00:30:19.330 --> 00:30:24.280
given the boundary conditions on
money and schedule and the era

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:27.951
that we built it, between 2001
and '05, what would you do

00:30:27.951 --> 00:30:28.450
differently?

00:30:28.450 --> 00:30:30.250
That means a zero sum game.

00:30:30.250 --> 00:30:33.340
You have to find the money,
the mass, the resources

00:30:33.340 --> 00:30:35.680
by taking something else off.

00:30:35.680 --> 00:30:40.330
And there's no instrument or
capability on New Horizons

00:30:40.330 --> 00:30:43.126
that we wish we would trade,
that we would lose in order

00:30:43.126 --> 00:30:44.000
to do something else.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:45.710
Now with the Orbiter,
which will be

00:30:45.710 --> 00:30:50.770
a much more capable spacecraft
and a much wider variety

00:30:50.770 --> 00:30:53.542
of payloads,
onboard instruments,

00:30:53.542 --> 00:30:55.000
we'll do lots of
things we couldn't

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:56.830
do with a simple flyby.

00:30:56.830 --> 00:31:02.059
But I wouldn't trade If I
really could just have my wish,

00:31:02.059 --> 00:31:03.850
it would have been that
we had enough money

00:31:03.850 --> 00:31:08.211
to fly two because the far side
of Pluto and its satellites,

00:31:08.211 --> 00:31:10.210
we can only see them from
millions of kilometers

00:31:10.210 --> 00:31:13.990
away as we were screaming up,
and then they turned away.

00:31:13.990 --> 00:31:15.220
And it's frustrating.

00:31:15.220 --> 00:31:17.020
You look at the
other side of Pluto

00:31:17.020 --> 00:31:20.810
and it looks completely
different and fascinating.

00:31:20.810 --> 00:31:23.230
And what does that
have to teach us?

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:26.080
And I'm really betting
on life extension

00:31:26.080 --> 00:31:29.500
so that I can BPI
that next mission.

00:31:29.500 --> 00:31:31.225
Yeah, right here.

00:31:31.225 --> 00:31:33.350
AUDIENCE: The mission was
a publicly funded success

00:31:33.350 --> 00:31:37.090
at a time when it's not clear
what the future holds for that.

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:38.674
What do you think
is likely to happen.

00:31:38.674 --> 00:31:40.756
What do you think should
happen in terms of public

00:31:40.756 --> 00:31:42.890
versus private funding
for the [INAUDIBLE]??

00:31:42.890 --> 00:31:45.460
ALAN STERN: Well, fortunately--
and everybody here probably

00:31:45.460 --> 00:31:50.740
knows this-- is that commercial
space is coming on very strong.

00:31:50.740 --> 00:31:54.560
And I admit I am
very highly biased.

00:31:54.560 --> 00:31:58.990
And I also happen to be the
board chair of the Commercial

00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:01.640
Space Flight Federation, which
is the industry federation

00:32:01.640 --> 00:32:06.830
that Blue Origin and
SpaceX and everybody else

00:32:06.830 --> 00:32:10.480
is in, 80 corporations, from
small mom and pop, almost,

00:32:10.480 --> 00:32:15.310
shops all the way up to
SpaceX and Blue Origin.

00:32:15.310 --> 00:32:17.890
But I think, again,
it's not a choice

00:32:17.890 --> 00:32:20.890
between one and the other.

00:32:20.890 --> 00:32:25.570
This is a huge solar system
with dozens of worlds.

00:32:25.570 --> 00:32:31.900
And I don't know how we would
do all the things that we

00:32:31.900 --> 00:32:35.980
do on the seas and in the air if
it was all done by just the Air

00:32:35.980 --> 00:32:38.320
Force and the Navy.

00:32:38.320 --> 00:32:40.630
And besides that, if
it's one organization,

00:32:40.630 --> 00:32:42.790
you can't possibly have
the level of innovation

00:32:42.790 --> 00:32:45.130
that you get
through competition.

00:32:45.130 --> 00:32:50.350
And so I think all that's going
on at places like Blue Origin

00:32:50.350 --> 00:32:54.250
and SpaceX and all the
others is it's finally

00:32:54.250 --> 00:32:57.370
the 21st century, where we don't
just have one space program,

00:32:57.370 --> 00:32:58.790
but lots of them.

00:32:58.790 --> 00:33:02.620
And now we're starting to
have the asteroid miners

00:33:02.620 --> 00:33:06.550
and the moon miners and
lots more applications being

00:33:06.550 --> 00:33:07.350
talked about.

00:33:07.350 --> 00:33:09.700
I think the 20s are going
to be just spectacular.

