to be doing in the 20s,

00:33:12.070 --> 00:33:17.140
which you would not see
commercial enterprises

00:33:17.140 --> 00:33:20.350
exploring Europa for
scientific knowledge.

00:33:20.350 --> 00:33:23.440
But you might see
commercial enterprises

00:33:23.440 --> 00:33:28.450
sending payloads to Mars
because they can find customers

00:33:28.450 --> 00:33:30.045
that want to fly those.

00:33:30.045 --> 00:33:32.170
So sort of the vanguard,
the leading edge, I think,

00:33:32.170 --> 00:33:36.790
is always going to be the
government in most respects.

00:33:36.790 --> 00:33:40.090
But private industry is what
comes in and really turns it

00:33:40.090 --> 00:33:44.080
into part of the
economy and what we do.

00:33:44.080 --> 00:33:46.060
And we need both.

00:33:46.060 --> 00:33:48.580
DAVID GRINSPOON: And nobody
at NASA that I know--

00:33:48.580 --> 00:33:50.470
we both know a lot
of people at NASA--

00:33:50.470 --> 00:33:53.680
nobody there is bummed
out that oh, now we

00:33:53.680 --> 00:33:56.050
have these competitors
from private industry.

00:33:56.050 --> 00:33:57.640
They're like, oh, great.

00:33:57.640 --> 00:33:59.440
We don't have to be
the trucking service up

00:33:59.440 --> 00:34:01.810
to orbit, or the bus service.

00:34:01.810 --> 00:34:04.760
We can focus on other things
that only NASA can do.

00:34:04.760 --> 00:34:07.720
And so the private
public partnership

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:10.659
is really being sought by
both sides in that equation

00:34:10.659 --> 00:34:15.429
and is shaping up to really
accelerate space exploration

00:34:15.429 --> 00:34:16.761
in this century.

00:34:16.761 --> 00:34:17.469
ALAN STERN: Yeah.

