analysis part of the project

00:36:21.780 --> 00:36:24.270
is still ongoing.

00:36:24.270 --> 00:36:27.600
But you know, the comet C-G,
the one with all the syllables,

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:30.240
is about the size
of Cambridge, Mass.

00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:32.670
And Pluto's the surface
area of the United States.

00:36:32.670 --> 00:36:34.320
So it's a different
scale, and the kind

00:36:34.320 --> 00:36:36.550
of science you're doing
is very different.

00:36:36.550 --> 00:36:38.240
Who else?

00:36:38.240 --> 00:36:39.130
Yep.

00:36:39.130 --> 00:36:41.958
AUDIENCE: What was the biggest--

00:36:41.958 --> 00:36:44.910
what was the most
frustrating mistake

00:36:44.910 --> 00:36:48.120
that you look back on of,
oh, we didn't do this right.

00:36:48.120 --> 00:36:50.030
If I could go back
and change one thing.

00:36:50.030 --> 00:36:52.550
What was the biggest takeaway?

00:36:52.550 --> 00:36:56.040
ALAN STERN: Wow,
that's a good question.

00:36:56.040 --> 00:36:58.110
I ought to say the
thing that nearly killed

00:36:58.110 --> 00:37:00.210
the spacecraft 10 days out.

00:37:00.210 --> 00:37:04.050
But it sure brought
a lot of viewership.

00:37:04.050 --> 00:37:07.792
The last minute, all of a
sudden it's life or death.

00:37:07.792 --> 00:37:09.750
DAVID GRINSPOON: There
were some other mistakes

00:37:09.750 --> 00:37:11.370
that we describe in the book.

00:37:11.370 --> 00:37:13.710
But fortunately none
of them were fatal

00:37:13.710 --> 00:37:17.210
because we have a success story.

00:37:17.210 --> 00:37:20.730
But they're illustrative.

00:37:20.730 --> 00:37:23.430
I mean, one thing you learn
in this book is how carefully

00:37:23.430 --> 00:37:26.640
everything was checked by
independent teams, and just

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:28.067
a lot of amazing
troubleshooting.

00:37:28.067 --> 00:37:29.400
And very little slipped through.

00:37:29.400 --> 00:37:32.340
But there was one
spreadsheet where

00:37:32.340 --> 00:37:37.620
one thruster had the wrong
specs and was built and flown

00:37:37.620 --> 00:37:39.300
with the wrong
specs so that it was

00:37:39.300 --> 00:37:43.530
going to fire too many times
and exhaust its lifetime

00:37:43.530 --> 00:37:44.820
before they got to Pluto.

00:37:44.820 --> 00:37:47.400
And they discovered this
when they were in flight.

00:37:47.400 --> 00:37:50.400
And they were able to
make some workarounds.

00:37:50.400 --> 00:37:52.590
But that was sort of
almost the exception

00:37:52.590 --> 00:37:54.420
that proves the
rule because there

00:37:54.420 --> 00:37:56.150
was almost nothing like that.

00:37:56.150 --> 00:37:58.110
But it was really
illustrative of why

00:37:58.110 --> 00:38:01.140
it was so important that they
do all that ridiculous amount

00:38:01.140 --> 00:38:04.170
of checking and double checking
because so little slipped

00:38:04.170 --> 00:38:04.740
through.

00:38:04.740 --> 00:38:07.435
But that was maybe
not the worst mistake,

00:38:07.435 --> 00:38:08.810
but it's an
illustrative mistake.

00:38:08.810 --> 00:38:09.518
ALAN STERN: Yeah.

00:38:09.518 --> 00:38:11.040
Yeah.

00:38:11.040 --> 00:38:11.540
I'm sorry.

00:38:11.540 --> 00:38:13.260
I really don't
have a good answer

00:38:13.260 --> 00:38:15.960
because most of the things
that I think I did wrong

00:38:15.960 --> 00:38:20.190
or we did wrong actually, in
the end, worked out better.

00:38:20.190 --> 00:38:23.970
So for example, if I could do
it again, some of the things

00:38:23.970 --> 00:38:26.310
I was doing in the
90s to lead the effort

00:38:26.310 --> 00:38:28.560
to get a mission to
Pluto, I think now,

00:38:28.560 --> 00:38:31.970
with more experience, I
could have made it happen.

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:33.810
But then I would have
just been a bit player

00:38:33.810 --> 00:38:36.400
on that mission instead of being
able to lead the whole thing.

00:38:36.400 --> 00:38:38.650
So I don't want to
make that happen.

00:38:38.650 --> 00:38:41.290
This was a lot more fun.

00:38:41.290 --> 00:38:42.337
Yeah, you go.

00:38:42.337 --> 00:38:44.670
AUDIENCE: I have a question
with regard to [INAUDIBLE]..

00:38:44.670 --> 00:38:48.710
A lot of the story here
revolves around politics

00:38:48.710 --> 00:38:49.995
and political struggle.

00:38:49.995 --> 00:38:52.470
And I was wondering, the fact
that Pluto, at some point,

00:38:52.470 --> 00:38:56.160
was demoted, was it part
of a political game?

00:38:56.160 --> 00:38:58.950
How could you explain it?

00:38:58.950 --> 00:39:01.640
ALAN STERN: I don't think
it was a political game.

00:39:01.640 --> 00:39:04.420
There are really two
things that were going on.

00:39:04.420 --> 00:39:07.849
One is, I think, appreciated
by a lot of people, which is--

00:39:07.849 --> 00:39:10.015
I think especially here,
you have the sophistication

00:39:10.015 --> 00:39:12.240
to know astronomers are
not planetary scientists.

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:13.640
Different expertise.

00:39:13.640 --> 00:39:17.070
When I give a public talk, I say
neurologists and podiatrists.

00:39:17.070 --> 00:39:19.357
Don't go to one for a
problem with the other.

00:39:19.357 --> 00:39:20.190
Different expertise.

00:39:20.190 --> 00:39:22.890
But people in the public,
including my own mother,

00:39:22.890 --> 00:39:26.160
confuses that all astronomers
must know everything

00:39:26.160 --> 00:39:27.720
about everything in space.

00:39:27.720 --> 00:39:31.710
They were really trying to cope
with large numbers of planet

00:39:31.710 --> 00:39:34.766
discoveries and thinking
in a 20th century way,

00:39:34.766 --> 00:39:36.390
I would say, that
the number of planets

00:39:36.390 --> 00:39:37.770
should be small
so schoolchildren

00:39:37.770 --> 00:39:38.811
can remember their names.

00:39:42.360 --> 00:39:45.779
I wish that they'd just
been consistent and gone on

00:39:45.779 --> 00:39:47.820
and had motions they'd
voted on other things they

00:39:47.820 --> 00:39:50.289
don't know about, and just
gone ahead and legislate it.

00:39:50.289 --> 00:39:52.830
We're only also going to have
eight elements and eight states

00:39:52.830 --> 00:39:53.730
now.

00:39:53.730 --> 00:39:54.780
But they didn't.

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:56.220
So the press picked up on it.

00:39:56.220 --> 00:40:01.290
And the press, also naively,
took it as expertise

00:40:01.290 --> 00:40:04.980
and sort of made
it a fait accompli,

00:40:04.980 --> 00:40:07.800
when people like David
and myself and others

00:40:07.800 --> 00:40:10.250
in planetary science,
a joining profession

00:40:10.250 --> 00:40:13.599
of a different expertise, never
said that, and don't buy it,

00:40:13.599 --> 00:40:15.140
and don't even buy
the idea of voting

00:40:15.140 --> 00:40:18.560
in science because it's sort
of an illegitimate process.

00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:21.960
We could all vote that the
theory of evolution is wrong.

00:40:21.960 --> 00:40:25.250
It doesn't matter how many
Nobel Laureates vote for it.

00:40:25.250 --> 00:40:29.090
That doesn't mean that the data
doesn't support the theory.

00:40:29.090 --> 00:40:31.850
The other thing that was going
on-- and it's very rarely

00:40:31.850 --> 00:40:37.490
discussed-- but it's the fact
that in 1980, an astronomer

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:40.520
named Brian Marsden, who
was very accomplished,

00:40:40.520 --> 00:40:43.580
had a very public with
the man who discovered

00:40:43.580 --> 00:40:46.490
Pluto named Clyde Tombaugh.

00:40:46.490 --> 00:40:49.550
And he actually
said at a meeting

00:40:49.550 --> 00:40:52.140
in front of a lot of people,
you're older than me,

00:40:52.140 --> 00:40:56.290
and when you're gone, I
will erase your legacy.

00:40:56.290 --> 00:40:59.750
And Marsden is the person
that led the IAU week

00:40:59.750 --> 00:41:04.580
to pass that resolution
which took Pluto

00:41:04.580 --> 00:41:07.430
off the astronomers' list.

00:41:07.430 --> 00:41:10.975
And so there's a
lot of bad blood.

00:41:10.975 --> 00:41:12.350
DAVID GRINSPOON:
Yeah, and if you

00:41:12.350 --> 00:41:18.650
look at the specific technical
description in the IAU's

00:41:18.650 --> 00:41:21.410
attempt at redefining
planet, just

00:41:21.410 --> 00:41:25.610
from a scientific,
quantitative perspective,

00:41:25.610 --> 00:41:27.390
it doesn't make any sense.

00:41:27.390 --> 00:41:29.150
They did a sloppy job.

00:41:29.150 --> 00:41:31.760
Well, for one thing, they said
a planet has to orbit the sun.

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:34.280
They ignored all the
exoplanets, which is ridiculous.

00:41:34.280 --> 00:41:36.890
But also even within
our own solar system,

00:41:36.890 --> 00:41:38.510
they had this
criterion that a planet

00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:41.510
must-- supposedly they said
it must clear its zone.

00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:43.400
So they defined
a planet in terms

00:41:43.400 --> 00:41:47.420
of what orbits around it and not
its own intrinsic properties.

00:41:47.420 --> 00:41:51.290
And that leads to some very
silly, absurd conclusions,

00:41:51.290 --> 00:41:55.190
like that Earth was not a planet
for its first 500 million years

00:41:55.190 --> 00:41:57.860
because it was orbiting in a
swarm of material left over

00:41:57.860 --> 00:41:59.270
from the formation of the sun.

00:41:59.270 --> 00:42:01.900
And if you took Earth today
and moved it somewhere else,

00:42:01.900 --> 00:42:03.980
say out in the asteroid
belt or something,

00:42:03.980 --> 00:42:06.060
it would not be a planet.

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:08.600
So there are a lot of just
sort of unsatisfying aspects

00:42:08.600 --> 00:42:09.710
of the definition.

00:42:09.710 --> 00:42:12.190
So it certainly
made sense to them

00:42:12.190 --> 00:42:15.560
to talk about classifying
Pluto and other small planets

00:42:15.560 --> 00:42:19.150
like it as a different subclass
of planets, dwarf planets.

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:19.895
That's fine.

00:42:19.895 --> 00:42:21.270
But then they sort
of added this,

00:42:21.270 --> 00:42:23.120
and a dwarf planet
is not a planet.

00:42:23.120 --> 00:42:25.760
And it was kind of
vindictive and nonsensical.

00:42:25.760 --> 00:42:28.770
And so in planetary
science, at our meetings,

00:42:28.770 --> 00:42:31.760
you'll hear us referring
to Pluto a planet.

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:34.280
And we almost kind
of don't really

00:42:34.280 --> 00:42:36.700
even want to talk about
this, except for it is worth

00:42:36.700 --> 00:42:38.450
talking about because
people are confused,

00:42:38.450 --> 00:42:39.650
and they want to know.

00:42:39.650 --> 00:42:41.710
And so we have to
try to clarify it.

00:42:41.710 --> 00:42:42.960
ALAN STERN: He said we
don't want to talk about it.

00:42:42.960 --> 00:42:45.168
But yesterday in "The
Washington Post", the two of us

00:42:45.168 --> 00:42:46.350
had an Op Ed.

00:42:46.350 --> 00:42:47.300
DAVID GRINSPOON: Yeah.

00:42:47.300 --> 00:42:50.922
AUDIENCE: So how many plants
are there on your list?

00:42:50.922 --> 00:42:52.130
DAVID GRINSPOON: Uncountable.

00:42:52.130 --> 00:42:55.800
ALAN STERN: So yeah,
that's really the answer.

00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:56.300
Oh, known?

00:42:56.300 --> 00:42:57.680
It's in the mid 20s.

00:42:57.680 --> 00:42:58.490
DAVID GRINSPOON: In
our solar system.

00:42:58.490 --> 00:42:59.510
ALAN STERN: In our solar system.

00:42:59.510 --> 00:43:01.593
But of course there are
thousands of known planets

00:43:01.593 --> 00:43:02.540
around other stars.

00:43:02.540 --> 00:43:04.890
But you know, who cares?

00:43:04.890 --> 00:43:06.890
There's countless mountains
and rivers and stars

00:43:06.890 --> 00:43:09.290
and asteroids and galaxies
and all those things.

00:43:09.290 --> 00:43:13.670
Space is all about, oh,
astronomical numbers.

00:43:13.670 --> 00:43:16.160
So we really need to
get over the notion.

00:43:16.160 --> 00:43:19.070
The notion that there were
a small number of planets,

00:43:19.070 --> 00:43:21.350
I think, is
equivalent to somebody

00:43:21.350 --> 00:43:22.850
who grew up on a
desert island where

00:43:22.850 --> 00:43:24.999
there were a countable
number of palm trees.

00:43:24.999 --> 00:43:26.540
And you think that's
it for the world

00:43:26.540 --> 00:43:28.302
because you don't see
any other islands.

00:43:28.302 --> 00:43:29.510
They're all over the horizon.

00:43:29.510 --> 00:43:33.620
Then you develop the
technology for ocean travel,

00:43:33.620 --> 00:43:35.130
and you can now go
to other places.

00:43:35.130 --> 00:43:39.440
And you discover that all those
trees, you gave them names.

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:41.630
There's so many you
can't name them all.

00:43:41.630 --> 00:43:43.130
So you decide those
aren't actually

00:43:43.130 --> 00:43:47.480
palm trees for whatever
reason, just to keep it small.

00:43:47.480 --> 00:43:48.810
So it's kind of crazy.

00:43:48.810 --> 00:43:49.310
OK.

00:43:49.310 --> 00:43:52.730
I guess we're going to say thank
you for coming out at lunch.

00:43:52.730 --> 00:43:54.580
[APPLAUSE]

